\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7556174 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5248227\charrsid6384043 
Many people divide society into different social classes or groups, in that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4860835 BR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5248227\charrsid6384043 
Well - generally - in this particular neighbourhood - there was - as far as I know there was - one - Mr - Downey that used to keep the pub, of course he was regarded as - somebody, although - my parents way of thinking he was just 
the same as me although he had the Castle and all that kind of thing - 'cos he had trotting ponies and all that kind of thing. And then there was a Mrs Williams. That's a lady that turned round and converted two houses in - for baths and all that. And of 
course we - we did look up to the - ministers and all that kind of thing down here. But otherwise everybody else was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7556174 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5248227\charrsid6384043 Working class you mentioned you thought?
